
## Context

IcePhone is an AI-powered CRM and Voice Agent Platform that allows business owners to set up custom Voice Agents to respond to inbound calls, perform outbound cold calls and follow-ups fully autonomously. It also provides standard CRM features for lead tracking, qualification, analytics, etc.

## Coding Style:

- Ideally, you should write simple solutions that do not need complex debugging / maintenance if things go wrong
- If you notice a lint error that you think is not important or critical, please turn it off in the .eslintrc.json file.
- Always assume the dev server is running.
- Follow modern best practices for full-stack web development in Next.js, keeping user privacy and security in mind.
- When editing a page to add new components, always make the components first and then add them to the page to avoid causing temporary errors.

## How to work with the Databse (Drizzle ORM + PostgreSQL)

- The schema location is `src/db/schema.ts`.
- Put all your server actions in `src/actions/(name).ts`
- Put all the types in `src/types.ts`
- After making changes to the schema, run `bun db:dev:push` or `bun db:prod:push` to generate and apply migrations to our neon database.
- Please try to use `mcp_run_sql_transaction` tool: wrap the commands that you are thinking of implementing in a transaction, and roll it back with a RETURNING clause to "preview" your changes before writing the drizzle code.
- This tool call allows you to "dry run" and test changes easily.

example:
```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION                                                    ;
UPDATE feedback SET rating = rating + 1 WHERE rating < 5 RETURNING * ;
ROLLBACK                                                             ;
```

This approach is very useful for debugging as well.

Note that in Next.js, we always prefer to use server actions instead of API routes, so that the code is simple to read and write.

## Clerk Authentication:

- The middleware is in src/middleware.ts - dont modify this file.
- Remember to use the appropriate helper to get the current user's id depending on server/client components.
- On the server side, use the `currentUser` helper from `@clerk/nextjs/server` to get the current users details.
- On the client side, use the `useUser` hook from `@clerk/nextjs` to get the current user's id.

## What to do when things go wrong:

- Run `bun filetree` to see the current file structure of the project (excludes node modules etc.)
- First, check the server and browser logs:
-- Server Logs are continously saved to `logs/server.log` file as they appear in the console. You can run `tail -n 200 server.log` for the latest logs of the current dev server session (the file is cleared each time before running `next dev`)
-- Browser logs can be fetched by calling the `mcp_getConsoleLogs()` tool. If you can't access them, remind me to run `bun browser-mcp` in a terminal and `right click -> inspect` on the page to open Chrome Dev Tools (which connects the MCP server to the browser)
- If debugging type errors, run `bun typecheck` after your changes to make sure everything works.
- If the problem could be related to a server side function that in any way interacts with the database, please try to use the `mcp_run_sql` tool from neon to interact with the db directly to understand the problem. After applying your changes, run the tool again to confirm that your solution has indeed worked.
- If you can solve an issue using Next.js features vs using features of external packages, try using the Next.js solution because it is usually less error prone. This is not always the case as there might be popular javascript packages that solve issues in a simple way.
- Always run commands to figure out things - I will always give you permission to run almost any terminal command because I want you to read the output from the terminal directly. This results in a faster feedback loop. Feel free to add packages, remove files, or anything else through the terminal. I will give you permission.
- If you think searching the web is a good idea to look for docs or any other up to date information, just do it.
- If you run into lint errors with Next.js or React, search the web for the most recent documentation for Next.js 15 / React 19

## Packages:

- Always use bun as the package manager to run commands instead of npm.
- Always use bunx instead of npx.

## Design and Styling:

- Always try to use UI components from shadcn/ui. It is already installed, but not all components are added. You can run the commands like `bunx shadcn@latest add button card` etc to add specific components. Run a search in the components folder before you run the install command to understand which ones you can skip.
- Always use Tailwind CSS for styling. It is already installed.
- Always use icons from lucide-react. It is already installed.
- Try to create clean, sleek, modern, and minimal design that is responsive on both mobile and desktop browsers.
- Follow the design patterns, conventions, and styling applied in the project to remain consistent.
- Always use rounded corners (2xl or 3xl).
- Prefer the 'outline' variant for most buttons.

## Tech Stack:

- Next.js v15 (App Router)
- React v19
- Tailwind CSS
- Drizzle ORM
- Neon Database (PostgresSQL)
- Shadcn/ui for components
- Clerk for authentication
- Lucide-react for icons
- Cloudflare for deployment

## Performance:

- My highest priority is User Experience.
- I want this Next.js website to load fast on any browser and in all network conditions.
- Try to use React Server Components whenever possible so that we can render pages on the server for faster initial page loads.
- However, if some components need high interactivity then you can use client components for a good user experience.
- It should react to user input quickly without any lag and feel "snappy" to use.
- I might give you some images to add to the site - always run a zsh command to convert it to an optimized format like webp before adding it so that they load fast.
